,"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","St Clement Danes,Westminster,Middlesex,England":"St Clement Danes, Westminster, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","Balweary, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (Down): habitational and ethnic name from Middle English <i>Scot</i> ‘man from Scotland’. There is no evidence that the surname denoted either of the earlier senses of <i>Scot</i> as ‘(Gaelic-speaking) Irishman’ or ‘man from Alba’, the Gaelic-speaking region of Scotland north of the river Forth. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English and Scottish: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Scot</i> (Old English <i>Scott</i>, possibly also Old Norse <i>Skotr</i>), only certainly attested in northern England.","English: variant of   Scutt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Scutt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Pierre.","Americanized form of Dutch   Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Scott of Balweary was born in 1350, in Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Andrew Scott - Fourth Lord of Balwearie, was 35 and his mother, Lady Isobel de Warren, was 40. He married Elizabeth Harborne in St Clement Danes, Westminster, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1406, in Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1350–1406":"1350–1406","1360–1454":"1360–1454","1350–1424":"1350–1424","1375–1440":"1375–1440","1389–1424":"1389–1424","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1315":"1315","1424":"1424","1389":"1389","1355":"1355","1454":"1454","Abt 1375":"umbes 1375","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1406":"1406","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","St Clement Danes,Westminster,Middlesex,England":"St Clement Danes, Westminster, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Balweary, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1350–1406":"1350–1406","1360–1454":"1360–1454","1350–1424":"1350–1424","1375–1440":"1375–1440","1389–1424":"1389–1424","1315–1355":"1315–1355","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1440":"1440","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1315":"1315","1424":"1424","1389":"1389","1355":"1355","1454":"1454","Abt 1375":"noin 1375","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1406":"1406","Balwearie Castle, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","St